plotTheme <- function(base_size = 12, title_size = 16) {
  theme(
    text = element_text( color = "black"),
    plot.title = element_text(size = title_size, colour = "black"), 
    plot.subtitle = element_text(face="italic"),
    plot.caption = element_text(hjust=0),
    axis.ticks = element_blank(),
    panel.background = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.major = element_line("grey80", size = 0.1),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
    panel.border = element_rect(colour = "black", fill=NA, size=2),
    strip.background = element_rect(fill = "grey80", color = "white"),
    strip.text = element_text(size=12),
    axis.title = element_text(size=12),
    axis.text = element_text(size=10),
    plot.background = element_blank(),
    legend.background = element_blank(),
    legend.title = element_text(colour = "black", face = "italic"),
    legend.text = element_text(colour = "black", face = "italic"),
    strip.text.x = element_text(size = 14)
  )
}

q5 <- function(variable) {as.factor(ntile(variable, 5))}

qBr <- function(df, variable, rnd) {
  if (missing(rnd)) {
    as.character(quantile(round(df[[variable]],0),
                          c(.01,.2,.4,.6,.8), na.rm=T))
  } else if (rnd == FALSE | rnd == F) {
    as.character(formatC(quantile(df[[variable]],
                                  c(.01,.2,.4,.6,.8), na.rm=T),
                         digits = 3))
  }
}

#this function converts a raster to a data frame that can be plotted
rast <- function(inRaster) {
  data.frame(
    xyFromCell(inRaster, 1:ncell(inRaster)), 
    value = getValues(inRaster)) }

##this is the nearest neighbor function
nn_function <- function(measureFrom,measureTo,k) {
  measureFrom_Matrix <-
    as.matrix(measureFrom)
  measureTo_Matrix <-
    as.matrix(measureTo)
  nn <-   
    get.knnx(measureTo, measureFrom, k)$nn.dist
  output <-
    as.data.frame(nn) %>%
    rownames_to_column(var = "thisPoint") %>%
    gather(points, point_distance, V1:ncol(.)) %>%
    arrange(as.numeric(thisPoint)) %>%
    group_by(thisPoint) %>%
    summarize(pointDistance = mean(point_distance)) %>%
    arrange(as.numeric(thisPoint)) %>% 
    dplyr::select(-thisPoint) %>%
    pull()
  
  return(output)  
}

# Multi-ring Buffer
multipleRingBuffer <- function(inputPolygon, maxDistance, interval) 
{
  #create a list of distances that we'll iterate through to create each ring
  distances <- seq(0, maxDistance, interval)
  #we'll start with the second value in that list - the first is '0'
  distancesCounter <- 2
  #total number of rings we're going to create
  numberOfRings <- floor(maxDistance / interval)
  #a counter of number of rings
  numberOfRingsCounter <- 1
  #initialize an otuput data frame (that is not an sf)
  allRings <- data.frame()
  
  #while number of rings  counteris less than the specified nubmer of rings
  while (numberOfRingsCounter <= numberOfRings) 
  {
    #if we're interested in a negative buffer and this is the first buffer
    #(ie. not distance = '0' in the distances list)
    if(distances[distancesCounter] < 0 & distancesCounter == 2)
    {
      #buffer the input by the first distance
      buffer1 <- st_buffer(inputPolygon, distances[distancesCounter])
      #different that buffer from the input polygon to get the first ring
      buffer1_ <- st_difference(inputPolygon, buffer1)
      #cast this sf as a polygon geometry type
      thisRing <- st_cast(buffer1_, "POLYGON")
      #take the last column which is 'geometry'
      thisRing <- as.data.frame(st_geometry(thisRing))
      #add a new field, 'distance' so we know how far the distance is for a give ring
      thisRing$distance <- distances[distancesCounter]
    }
    
    
    #otherwise, if this is the second or more ring (and a negative buffer)
    else if(distances[distancesCounter] < 0 & distancesCounter > 2) 
    {
      #buffer by a specific distance
      buffer1 <- st_buffer(inputPolygon, distances[distancesCounter])
      #create the next smallest buffer
      buffer2 <- st_buffer(inputPolygon, distances[distancesCounter-1])
      #This can then be used to difference out a buffer running from 660 to 1320
      #This works because differencing 1320ft by 660ft = a buffer between 660 & 1320.
      #bc the area after 660ft in buffer2 = NA.
      thisRing <- st_difference(buffer2,buffer1)
      #cast as apolygon
      thisRing <- st_cast(thisRing, "POLYGON")
      #get the last field
      thisRing <- as.data.frame(st_geometry(thisRing))
      #create the distance field
      thisRing$distance <- distances[distancesCounter]
    }
    
    #Otherwise, if its a positive buffer
    else 
    {
      #Create a positive buffer
      buffer1 <- st_buffer(inputPolygon, distances[distancesCounter])
      #create a positive buffer that is one distance smaller. So if its the first buffer
      #distance, buffer1_ will = 0. 
      buffer1_ <- st_buffer(inputPolygon, distances[distancesCounter-1])
      #difference the two buffers
      thisRing <- st_difference(buffer1,buffer1_)
      #cast as a polygon
      thisRing <- st_cast(thisRing, "POLYGON")
      #geometry column as a data frame
      thisRing <- as.data.frame(st_geometry(thisRing))
      #add teh distance
      thisRing$distance <- distances[distancesCounter]
    }  
    
    #rbind this ring to the rest of the rings
    allRings <- rbind(allRings, thisRing)
    #iterate the distance counter
    distancesCounter <- distancesCounter + 1
    #iterate the number of rings counter
    numberOfRingsCounter <- numberOfRingsCounter + 1
  }
  
  #convert the allRings data frame to an sf data frame
  allRings <- st_as_sf(allRings)
}

# Cross-validate function from chapter 5 (left in chapter)
crossValidate <- function(dataset, id, dependentVariable, indVariables) {
  
  allPredictions <- data.frame()
  cvID_list <- unique(dataset[[id]])
  
  for (i in cvID_list) {
    
    thisFold <- i
    cat("This hold out fold is", thisFold, "\n")
    
    fold.train <- filter(dataset, dataset[[id]] != thisFold) %>% as.data.frame() %>% 
      dplyr::select(id, geometry, all_of(indVariables),
                    all_of(dependentVariable))
    fold.test  <- filter(dataset, dataset[[id]] == thisFold) %>% as.data.frame() %>% 
      dplyr::select(id, geometry, all_of(indVariables),
                    all_of(dependentVariable))
    
    form_parts <- paste0(dependentVariable, " ~ ", paste0(indVariables, collapse = "+"))
    form <- as.formula(form_parts)
    regression <- glm(form, family = "poisson",
                      data = fold.train %>%
                        dplyr::select(-geometry, -id))
    
    thisPrediction <-
      mutate(fold.test, Prediction = predict(regression, fold.test, type = "response"))
    
    allPredictions <-
      rbind(allPredictions, thisPrediction)
    
  }
  return(st_sf(allPredictions))
}


# Iterate Thresholds Chapter 6, 7 (left in Chapters)
iterateThresholds <- function(data, observedClass, predictedProbs, group) {
  #This function takes as its inputs, a data frame with an observed binomial class (1 or 0); a vector of predicted #probabilities; and optionally a group indicator like race. It returns accuracy plus counts and rates of confusion matrix #outcomes. It's a bit verbose because of the if (missing(group)). I don't know another way to make an optional parameter.
  observedClass <- enquo(observedClass)
  predictedProbs <- enquo(predictedProbs)
  group <- enquo(group)
  x = .01
  all_prediction <- data.frame()
  
  if (missing(group)) {
    
    while (x <= 1) {
      this_prediction <- data.frame()
      
      this_prediction <-
        data %>%
        mutate(predclass = ifelse(!!predictedProbs > x, 1,0)) %>%
        count(predclass, !!observedClass) %>%
        summarize(Count_TN = sum(n[predclass==0 & !!observedClass==0]),
                  Count_TP = sum(n[predclass==1 & !!observedClass==1]),
                  Count_FN = sum(n[predclass==0 & !!observedClass==1]),
                  Count_FP = sum(n[predclass==1 & !!observedClass==0]),
                  Rate_TP = Count_TP / (Count_TP + Count_FN),
                  Rate_FP = Count_FP / (Count_FP + Count_TN),
                  Rate_FN = Count_FN / (Count_FN + Count_TP),
                  Rate_TN = Count_TN / (Count_TN + Count_FP),
                  Accuracy = (Count_TP + Count_TN) / 
                    (Count_TP + Count_TN + Count_FN + Count_FP)) %>%
        mutate(Threshold = round(x,2))
      
      all_prediction <- rbind(all_prediction,this_prediction)
      x <- x + .01
    }
    return(all_prediction)
  }
  else if (!missing(group)) { 
    while (x <= 1) {
      this_prediction <- data.frame()
      
      this_prediction <-
        data %>%
        mutate(predclass = ifelse(!!predictedProbs > x, 1,0)) %>%
        group_by(!!group) %>%
        count(predclass, !!observedClass) %>%
        summarize(Count_TN = sum(n[predclass==0 & !!observedClass==0]),
                  Count_TP = sum(n[predclass==1 & !!observedClass==1]),
                  Count_FN = sum(n[predclass==0 & !!observedClass==1]),
                  Count_FP = sum(n[predclass==1 & !!observedClass==0]),
                  Rate_TP = Count_TP / (Count_TP + Count_FN),
                  Rate_FP = Count_FP / (Count_FP + Count_TN),
                  Rate_FN = Count_FN / (Count_FN + Count_TP),
                  Rate_TN = Count_TN / (Count_TN + Count_FP),
                  Accuracy = (Count_TP + Count_TN) / 
                    (Count_TP + Count_TN + Count_FN + Count_FP)) %>%
        mutate(Threshold = round(x,2))
      
      all_prediction <- rbind(all_prediction,this_prediction)
      x <- x + .01
    }
    return(all_prediction)
  }
}

# Iterate Fairness Chapter 7 (left in chapter)
iterateFairness <- function(data, regression, threshold.by) {
  #create a table of all possible threshold combinations and input how many different thresholds to test.
  all.combos <- expand.grid(group1 = seq(0.1 , 1, threshold.by), group2 = seq(0.1,1 ,threshold.by))
  all_prediction <- data.frame()
  #while `counter` is less than the number of possible threshold combinations 
  counter = 1
  while (counter <= nrow(all.combos)) {
    this_prediction <- data.frame()
    #choose the next i thresholds    
    group1.thresh <- all.combos[counter,1]
    group2.thresh <- all.combos[counter,2]
    #create a temporary table that includes the predicted probability    
    this_prediction <- data.frame(
      observed = data[["Recidivated"]],
      probs = predict(regression, data, type="response"),
      race = data[["race"]]) %>%
      mutate(predicted = 
               case_when(race == "African-American" & probs >= group1.thresh  ~ "Recidivate",
                         race == "Caucasian" & probs >= group2.thresh  ~ "Recidivate",
                         TRUE ~"notRecidivate"),
             predicted = as.factor(predicted)) %>%
      #calculate fairness metrics
      group_by(race) %>%
      count(predicted,observed) %>%
      summarize(True_Negative = sum(n[predicted=="notRecidivate" & observed=="notRecidivate"]),
                True_Positive = sum(n[predicted=="Recidivate" & observed=="Recidivate"]),
                False_Negative = sum(n[predicted=="notRecidivate" & observed=="Recidivate"]),
                False_Positive = sum(n[predicted=="Recidivate" & observed=="notRecidivate"]),
                False_Positive_Rate = False_Positive / (False_Positive + True_Negative),
                False_Negative_Rate = False_Negative / (False_Negative + True_Positive),
                Accuracy = (True_Negative + True_Positive) /  
                  (True_Negative + True_Positive + False_Negative + False_Positive)) %>%
      mutate(threshold = paste(group1.thresh, group2.thresh, sep=", "))
    #store this outcome on a larger table
    all_prediction <- rbind(all_prediction,this_prediction)
    #iterate     
    counter <- counter + 1
  }
  #return fairness metrics for all threshold combinations
  return(all_prediction)
}

Introduction

The purpose of this project is to develop an accurate predictive model for housing prices in Philadelphia County, Pennsylvania. Though Philadelphia is still a relatively affordable city when compared to the other major cities in the U.S., the local housing market has picked up considerably in recent years, boosted by population growth and a relatively dense urban fabric with limited options for expanding housing stock. These factors present opportunities for investors, though they are also cause for concern in light of sustained increases in prices and the resulting pressure for local residents. This situation calls for a closer look that may provide valuable insights for investors, government agencies and homeowners.

To develop our predictive model we will use machine learning to analyze observed home prices and a range of available data on variables that affect housing prices. We will consider three kinds of factors:

  1. intrinsic characteristics of the housing units, such as total livable area or number of bathrooms;
  2. extrinsic characteristics of the housing units, such as proximity to public services and (dis)amenities (for example, crime);
  3. the spatial process of prices, by identifying house prices clustered at varying spatial scales.

In considering these data points we will try to account for the wide variety of factors that affect housing prices in different ways.

Notably, we will try to account for the “spatial relativity” of some variables.

The results of our analysis indicate that the predictive model developed for housing prices in Philadelphia County performs moderately well. The model incorporates a broad range of factors, including property characteristics, neighborhood amenities, and spatial attributes. While the model offers valuable insights into housing price trends, it is not without limitations.

Local Amenities & Disamenities

This includes: - Schools - Trees - Crime

The point data on amenities and disamenities is used to include an assessment of extrinsic characteristics of the housing units. For each house on sale, we considered the 5 nearest locations for each of the amenities/disamenities and calculated the ‘average nearest neighbor distance’. Unlike other methods such as using buffers, this approach minimizes scale biases in the use of point data for phenomena that don’t have a uniform spatial distribution.

Exploratory Analysis

Based on the nature of the variables, we categorized them into “internal characteristics,” “amenities/public services,” or “spatial structure.”

Internal Characteristics: These variables typically describe inherent characteristics of entities (e.g., houses, individuals) within the dataset. We included size, age, or number of bedrooms in a house.

Amenities/Public Services: Variables related to public amenities or services available in the dataset, such as schools, parks, or transportation options.

Spatial Structure: Variables related to the spatial organization or structure of the dataset, including geographical coordinates, boundaries, or distances.

Distribution of Dependent Variable- Sale Price

We noticed a wide variation in the sale prices - from a minimum of $10,100 to a maximum of $5,990,000.

We chose to transform the sale price variable due to the substantial variability within the dataset, indicating a wide dispersion of values.

While the median sale price of $229,900 suggested a typical price point for the middle property in the dataset, the mean sale price was slightly elevated, likely due to the influence of a few higher-priced properties.

This discrepancy between the mean and median suggests potential outliers or skewness in the data’s distribution.

By log-transforming the sale price variable, we aim to address these issues, making the data distribution more suitable for analysis, reducing the influence of extreme values, and helping ensure that statistical assumptions are met.

### HISTOGRAM

Correlation

Presented below is a correlation matrix that provides insights into the pairwise correlations between different sets of features in our dataset.

In this matrix, darker shades of blue signify a stronger positive correlation between the variable in the column and its corresponding variable in the row, while darker shades of pink indicate a more pronounced negative correlation.

Spatial Lag

Spatial lag is crucial for price predictions as it addresses the spatial dependence inherent in property data. Spatial autocorrelation, where similar values cluster in close proximity, is common in real estate, and failing to consider it can lead to biased parameter estimates and underestimated variability in prices. The inclusion of spatial lag variables captures the influence of neighboring property prices, reflecting local effects and improving prediction accuracy. By accounting for spatial relationships, models become more realistic, providing a better understanding of how prices are distributed across space. The creation of a lagged variable lagSalePrice helps incorporate information about nearby property prices into predictive models, enhancing their ability to capture spatial patterns and deliver more accurate predictions for property prices.

Methodology

We utilized Ordinary Least Squares (OLS) regression as our chosen method for predicting sale prices.

OLS is a widely-used statistical technique for estimating the coefficients of linear regression equations, which help us understand the relationship between one or more independent quantitative variables and a dependent variable.

In our case, we aimed to establish a meaningful correlation between home sale prices and various factors, such as income, crime, and presence of amenities (cafes, schools, trees).

In this particular model, we applied a log-transformation to the sale price variable. This transformation allowed us to create a distribution that is suitable for this type of regression analysis and also bound the values within a reasonable range.

This step was important, especially when dealing with extremely high sale prices, as it helped to mitigate their influence on the model’s performance.

The model itself was constructed using a random sample comprising 70% of the data, which we referred to as the training dataset. The remaining 30% of the data served as the test dataset, where we evaluated how well the model performed when applied to unseen data.

To assess the model’s effectiveness, we employed various error metrics, which provided insights into the model’s accuracy and precision.

Additionally, we conducted an investigation into the spatial patterns associated with errors and sale prices.

This spatial analysis allowed us to better understand any geographical dependencies and patterns within the dataset, providing valuable insights into the spatial process related to our predictions and errors.

Training Model for Actual Sale Price lm_model:

Significant Variables:

  1. Interior Condition: The coefficients for different levels of interior condition indicate how they affect the sale price compared to the reference level (not specified). Levels 4, 5, and 7 show a significant negative impact on sale price.

  2. Exterior Condition: Levels 2 to 7 of exterior condition significantly impact sale prices, with higher levels having a more negative effect.

  3. Fireplaces: Increasing the number of fireplaces positively influences sale prices, with each additional fireplace contributing to a higher sale price.

  4. Total Livable Area: The positive coefficient indicates that larger livable areas are associated with higher sale prices.

  5. Number of Bathrooms: More bathrooms positively influence sale prices.

  6. Cafes Buffer, Trees Buffer, Crimes Buffer: Proximity to cafes and trees positively affects sale prices, while crimes in the vicinity have a negative impact.

  7. Median Household Income: Higher median household income positively correlates with higher sale prices.

  8. Percentage White Population and Percentage with a Degree: Both variables have positive coefficients, indicating a positive relationship with sale prices.

  9. Vacancy Percentage: A higher vacancy percentage has a negative impact on sale prices.

  10. Housing Density: Higher housing density is associated with higher sale prices.

  11. Redlining Categories (B, C, D, NA): Presence in certain redlining categories, specifically B and NA, positively influences sale prices.

  12. Lagged Sale Price: The lagged sale price is positively associated with the current sale price.

  13. Schools Buffer: Proximity to schools negatively influences sale prices.

Model Evaluation:

  • Adjusted R-squared: The R-squared value of 0.7372 suggests that the model explains approximately 73.72% of the variance in sale prices.

  • F-statistic: The F-statistic tests the overall significance of the model, and the extremely low p-value (< 0.00000000000000022) indicates that the model is statistically significant.

The model suggests that features such as interior and exterior condition, amenities like fireplaces, neighborhood characteristics, and socioeconomic factors significantly influence property sale prices. The model has a good fit, as indicated by the high R-squared value, and the individual coefficients provide insights into the impact of each variable on the sale price.

Test Set

Mean Absolute Error (MAE) of $67,151.95 signifies the average absolute difference between the predicted sale prices and the actual observed prices. In the context of housing prices, this means that, on average, the model’s predictions deviate by approximately $67,151.95 from the actual sale prices.

Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE) of 4.00% indicates the average percentage difference between the predicted and observed sale prices. The model’s predictions, on average, deviate by approximately 4% from the actual sale prices. This suggests that the model’s predictions are, on average, close to the observed prices.

Map of Residuals with Moran’s I

Moran I Statistic: The Moran I statistic value is approximately 0.8872. This value ranges from -1 to 1. A positive Moran I value (like this one) indicates positive spatial autocorrelation, suggesting that locations with similar observed values are clustered together. This could mean that properties with similar sale prices tend to be located near each other.

The expectation (E) is approximately -0.0002103. If there were no spatial patterns in the data, we would expect the Moran I statistic to be close to this value.

The variance (Var) is approximately 0.00005608 which suggests that the Moran I statistic is relatively consistent, with low variance.

P-Value: The extremely small p-value (p < 0.00000000000000022) indicates that the observed spatial autocorrelation is highly significant. There is strong evidence that spatial clustering of sale prices is present in the data.

The results suggest that in the context of the Zillow use case, properties with similar sale prices tend to be spatially clustered, and this spatial autocorrelation is highly significant, not occurring by random chance.

Discussion

The results of the analysis shows that the model developed for predicting property sale prices in the context of the Zillow use case is reasonably effective, but there are some important considerations to take into account. The model’s effectiveness can be assessed from several angles.

First, the model’s ability to predict prices is moderate but not exceptional. The multiple R-squared value of approximately 44.68% suggests that the predictor variables included in the model collectively explain about 44.68% of the variation in property sale prices. This means that the model captures some, but not all, of the factors influencing property prices. Additionally, the Mean Absolute Error (MAE) of approximately $93,574.48 indicates that the model’s predictions, on average, deviate by this amount from the actual sale prices. The MAE suggests a certain degree of error in the model’s predictions, although the errors are reasonably consistent and can be accounted for.

Some of the more interesting variables in the model include "interior_condition," "Cafes.Buffer," "Trees.Buffer," "crimes.Buffer," "med_HH_Income.2021," "pctWhite," "pctDegree," and "pctVacant." These variables were found to have statistically significant effects on sale prices. The spatial analysis revealed that properties with similar sale prices tend to be clustered together, as indicated by the positive Moran’s I statistic. The presence of significant spatial autocorrelation implies that sale prices are not randomly distributed but tend to be geographically clustered.

The model seems to predict particularly well in areas where property prices exhibit spatial clustering, which aligns with the spatial autocorrelation findings. It may perform poorly in regions with highly heterogeneous property markets or where other unaccounted-for factors play a significant role. The reasons for variations in predictive accuracy may include factors not considered in the model, temporal changes in property market dynamics, or the influence of neighborhood-specific variables not accounted for. To improve the model’s performance, further exploration of additional relevant variables and refinement of the modeling approach may be necessary.

Conclusion

The model developed for predicting property sale prices in the context of the Zillow use case provides valuable insights into the factors influencing property values. While the model exhibits moderate effectiveness in explaining variations in sale prices, there are areas for consideration before recommending its implementation to Zillow.

The model’s strengths lie in its ability to capture significant predictors such as property condition, neighborhood features, income, and demographics, which collectively explain a substantial portion of the variance in sale prices. The presence of spatial clustering, as indicated by Moran’s I, aligns with the geographic nature of real estate markets. This provides valuable information for Zillow to understand localized property value dynamics.

However, the model has room for improvement. The Mean Absolute Error (MAE) of approximately $67,000 suggests that there is still notable room for error in the predictions. The model may perform better in areas with spatial clustering of sale prices but could be less accurate in heterogeneous markets. To enhance the model’s performance, Zillow should consider the inclusion of additional relevant variables, exploration of more advanced modeling techniques, and regular updates to account for changing real estate market dynamics.

To further enhance the model:

Additional Variables: Explore additional relevant variables that may contribute to price variation. Temporal Adjustments: Incorporate temporal adjustments to account for changes in market dynamics. Geographical Considerations: Address variations in predictive accuracy in different geographical contexts.

Ultimately, we would recommend the model to Zillow as a valuable tool for understanding property value determinants and for guiding pricing strategies. However, it should be seen as a starting point rather than a definitive pricing tool. The model, when continually refined and updated, can become an essential component in Zillow’s real estate valuation toolkit.

Training Model for Log(Sale Price) lm_model_log:

The model is constructed using the training data and predicts the log of sale prices (log_sale_price). The residual standard error is 0.376, which represents the typical magnitude of residuals. The model was built using 27 predictor variables and 18,760 degrees of freedom.

Residuals:

Min: The minimum residual is -7.6905. This represents the largest underestimation by the model, meaning there are instances where the model predicted prices that were significantly lower than the actual log sale prices.

1Q: The first quartile of residuals is -0.1214, indicating that 25% of the residuals are below this value. This implies that, in some cases, the model underestimates the log sale prices by this amount.

Median: The median residual is 0.0620, which represents the middle value of the residuals. The median residual suggests that, on average, the model underestimates the log sale prices by this amount.

3Q: The third quartile of residuals is 0.2061, meaning 75% of the residuals are below this value. In these cases, the model underestimates the log sale prices but to a lesser extent than the median underestimation.

Max: The maximum residual is 1.7229, indicating the largest overestimation by the model. Some predictions were substantially higher than the actual log sale prices.

Coefficients: sale_price.x, total_area, year_built, cafe_nn1, cafe_nn2, total_pop.2021, med_HH_Income.2021, pctWhite, pctDegree, and pctVacant have statistically significant effects on the predicted log sale prices, as indicated by their low p-values.

The coefficients of variables like tree_nn1 to tree_nn5 and crime_nn1 to crime_nn5 have less significance, with p-values above the typical significance threshold of 0.05.

Multiple R-squared: The multiple R-squared value is 0.7534, indicating that approximately 75.34% of the variance in the log sale prices can be explained by the predictor variables included in the model.

F-statistic: The extremely low p-value (< 0.00000000000000022) suggests that the model is statistically significant and fits the data well.
